Time Series Project¶

Problem Statement¶

In food retail forecast plays a big role in retail, getting it right will ensure you have the right availability and minimal waste. Getting it wrong will result in shortages or potentially high waste either one will reduce profit.

So, it’s quite valuable to be able to have insight on the trend history and how the market is changing to be able to prepare for the future.

Some of the interesting products we have in foods are seasonal performing lines, its vital to get the forecast right as any major over or under predictions could adversely affect the success of the season. We will be looking to model the forecast of the seasonally performing product group burgers. We will look at the data at weekly level to predict future trends and highlighting peaking periods. We will also further include weather in our model to make it multivariate model.

Time series is a great method to tackle this question as it helps us understand the past and help predict the future. We can reveal patterns by plotting data against time as we have one data point for every time period and each time period is equally spaced from each other. Hopefully this would predict the trend and seasonal pattern.

My initial expectations are sales in the burgers product group to increase when weather is hot with sunshine and around major sporting events. I also expect the sales to drop when the weather is cold and rainy.

Hypothesis¶

Null hypothesis:

1- There is a visible trend or seasonal pattern.

2- Is the visible seasonal pattern in shape with weather.

Alternative hypothesis:

1-There is no visible trend or seasonal pattern

2- There is no shape between the seasonal and weather pattern.

Overview¶

The initial plan for the project is as follows:

  1. Source the data
  2. Explore & clean the data
  3. Prepare the data for analysis
  4. Analyse the data
  5. Evaluate the model
  6. Improve the model

Source the data¶

The data was sourced from our Enterprise analytics hub using sql and exported as a csv. The data is for the last 3 years at daily level but was aggregated up to super product group level from product level. Weather data was also collected for the same period and then joined to the original data set. Initial thoughts about potential issues:

  • Our data will be able to show the peak and troughs in sales and weather, and potentially explain the troughs with peaking weather. I feel our issue will arise when sales are explained by external events outside our model like events that could likely cause a peak in sales which wouldn’t be explained by our model.

In terms of sharing issues, we don’t have much sensitive data, only sales quantity. The rest of the data is public such as calendar and weather.

Explore & clean the data¶

Initially the idea was to explore, clean and then prepare the data but due to issue while exploring It was decided to merge the exploring and the cleaning process into one.

Prepare the data¶

Decomposition¶

Time series is built up of components that can be categorised into systemic or non-systemic components where the former has consistency or occurrence and can be modelled and the later cannot be modelled. Systemic components are trend and seasonality and non-systemic component is noise. Time series can be combined by adding these three components to create an additive time series or multiplied to create a multiplicative time series. Multiplicative time series can be transformed to an additive by taking the log.

Decomposition is the process of deconstructing the three components trend, seasonality and noise.

Model and transform¶

Before we run our model, we need to confirm if our data is stationary, which means that over time the mean should be constant, covariance or standard deviation should be constant, or auto-covariance should not depend on time. Trend and seasonality are the two components that cause time series to not be stationary. If a model is stationary that means its behaviour over a time interval may repeat again, which helps forecast accurately.

To test for stationarity, we can run a simple KPSS test. This test assumes a null hypothesis that a time series is stationary. That means, if the p-value of the test is less than 0.05, we can reject this hypothesis and assume the data is not stationary.

Analyse the Data¶

ARIMA model

ARIMA stands for an AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average Model. It explicitly serves a group of standard structures in time series data providing a simple and powerful method for making skilful time series forecasts. There are three aspects of the model:

  1. Autoregression. A model that uses the dependent relationship between an observation and some number of lagged observations.
  2. Integrated. The use of differencing of raw observations in order to make the time series stationary.
  3. Moving Average. A model that uses the dependency between an observation and a residual error from a moving average model applied to lagged observations. Each of these components are explicitly specified in the model as a parameter. A standard notation is used of ARIMA(p,d,q) where the parameters are substituted with integer values to quickly indicate the specific ARIMA model being used.

The ARIMA parameters:

  1. p: The number of lag observations included in the model, also called the lag order.
  2. d: The number of times that the raw observations are differenced, also called the degree of differencing.
  3. q: The size of the moving average window, also called the order of moving average.
In [52]:
# importing relevant libraries
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_model import ARIMA
In [53]:
# This method finds the MSE of a single ARIMA model.
def evaluate_arima_model(nd, arima_order):
    split=int(len(nd) * 0.8) # Needs to be an integer because it is later used as an index.
    train, test = nd[0:split], nd[split:len(nd)]
    past=[x for x in train]
    # make predictions
    predictions = list()
    for i in range(len(test)):#timestep-wise comparison between test data and one-step prediction ARIMA model. 
        model = ARIMA(past, order=arima_order)
        model_fit = model.fit(disp=0)
        future = model_fit.forecast()[0]
        predictions.append(future)
        past.append(test[i])
    # calculate out of sample error
    error = mean_squared_error(test, predictions)
    return error
In [54]:
# This method evaluates ARIMA models with several different p, d, and q values.
def evaluate_models(dataset, p_values, d_values, q_values):
    best_score, best_cfg = float("inf"), None
    for p in p_values:
        for d in d_values:
            for q in q_values:
                order = (p,d,q)
                try:
                    mse = evaluate_arima_model(dataset, order)
                    if mse < best_score:
                        best_score, best_cfg = mse, order
                    print('ARIMA%s MSE=%.3f' % (order,mse))
                except:
                    continue
    return print('Best ARIMA%s MSE=%.3f' % (best_cfg, best_score))

Evaluate the model¶

We have looked at the sales of burgers from April 2016 until the current date to build a model that will predict sales for the next year. Looking at our data we can see we have a strong seasonality with peaks in summer and troughs in winter with an overall downwards trend.

After using our Arima model we plot our prediction against our differenced data, and we can see a straight upward trend line. This seems a bit unusual as our original data showed peaks and troughs and a downward trend. Once we plot the predictions against the original data, we can see that the prediction makes a bit more sense as it's predicting the upward trend of a given cycle.

We can clearly see that the ARIMA model is not fit to predict our data due to the core attribute of seasonality. We must look at a different model.

Seasonal Model¶

SARIMAX model

Seasonal AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average with eXogenous regressors model which is an extension of ARIMA that explicitly supports univariate time series data with a seasonal component. It adds three new hyperparameters to specify the autoregression (AR), differencing (I) and moving average (MA) for the seasonal component of the series, as well as an additional parameter for the period of the seasonality.

# creating the train and validation set
train = multi[:'2019-12']
valid = multi['2018-11':]

# fit the model
from statsmodels.tsa.vector_ar.var_model import VAR

model = VAR(endog=train)
model_fit = model.fit()

# make prediction on validation
prediction = model_fit.forecast(model_fit.y, steps=len(valid))

Evaluating the model¶

Looking at the outcome plot we can see the VAR model has successfully predicted sales and the weather with seasonality and trend. We couldn’t see the temperature on one plot due to y axis values, so we decided to plot the weather by itself to see the predictions and we can see that it has also successfully predicted it as well as the sales.
